## Step 3.7 — Principles and extensions

<!-- FILL IN: One sub-step-A/B/C paragraph block per group, every tier (EXCEPT summary-level groups in scale-gated syntheses) -->
<!-- CONTESTED groups get TWO blocks (one per side of contradiction) — see CONTESTED variant example below -->
<!-- GAP groups use the GAP variant — see GAP variant example below -->
<!-- Failure mode: if Sub-step A restates the finding rather than extracting a principle — retry -->

### [Group name] — [Tier: HIGH or CONSENSUS] (standard variant)

**A — Principle extracted:**
[The underlying principle, more general and abstract than the finding itself. Must apply to contexts the finding didn't test.]

**B — Fit to our setup:**
Tested in: [setup]. Our setup differs in: [specific differences]. Principle still applies because: [mechanism]. Principle may not apply if: [specific condition].

**C — Derivation beyond the finding:**
The principle implies that [X] would also [work / fail], even though the research didn't test it, because [mechanism]. Confidence in this derivation: [low/medium/high — reason].

### [Group name] — CONTESTED (CONTESTED variant — use this when Tier = CONTESTED)

**Side A — [label the side, e.g., "assertive-correction side"]**

**A — Principle extracted (Side A):**
[What principle holds true if Side A is correct? More general than the finding.]

**B — Fit to our setup (Side A):**
Side A would dominate our context if: [specific condition that would make Side A the right model]. Tested in: [Side A's research setup].

**C — Derivation (Side A):**
If Side A holds, then [X] would also follow, because [mechanism]. Confidence: [low/medium/high].

**Side B — [label the side, e.g., "approval-paradox side"]**

**A — Principle extracted (Side B):**
[What principle holds true if Side B is correct?]

**B — Fit to our setup (Side B):**
Side B would dominate our context if: [specific condition]. Tested in: [Side B's research setup].

**C — Derivation (Side B):**
If Side B holds, then [Y] would also follow. Confidence: [low/medium/high].

**Design signal:** The CONTESTED pair names a real tension to navigate: [what decision the user must make to resolve which side applies].

### [Group name] — GAP (GAP variant — use this when Tier = GAP)

**A — Principle from adjacent evidence:**
If evidence on [gap topic] existed, the principle WOULD likely be: [derived from adjacent findings or first principles]. Basis: [adjacent claims or first-principles reasoning].

**B — What the absence tells us:**
The gap is [expected / surprising given adjacent evidence]. This tells us: [what the field has or hasn't studied].

**C — Is the gap researchable?**
Yes — the angle would be: [specific research question]. OR: No — because [reason the gap may not be empirically accessible].

### [Next group] ...

